text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
from left to right, top to bottom: alexandria ocasio-cortez, ayana pressley, kristi noem, sharice davids, sylvia garcia, jahana hayes, ilhan omar, deb haaland, veronica escobar, rashida tlaib, janet mills and marsha blackburn.

by john hilliardglobe correspondent  november 07, 2018

the impact of tuesday’s election will be a topic of much debate, but one thing’s clear: women made big strides.
at least 99 women will represent americans in the house, surpassing the previous record of 84.
the associated press reported that 237 women ran for the house as major-party candidates in 2018, spurred in many cases by the #metoo movement and a renewed interest in politics following the 2016 election of president donald trump, whose attitudes toward women have been questioned.

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text: on july 19th, 2018 our world was changed forever. on the second day of supervised visitation clara came home with injuries obviously related to sexual assault. just one week before this the union county court ordered me to hand clara over to be supervised at 4 hour increments for visitation. with my heart broken i obeyed. july 19th was the second visitation. she was very sensitive in nature that evening so the discovery was not originally made until the next morning after she had calmed down enough for me to examine. i immediately went to the er and started this heart wrenching process with my 2 year old. the minute the attending pa examined her, the sane nurse was called in. i was encouraged by this sane nurse that i needed to push this investigation and that i had absolutely done the right thing. today, after nearly 4 months of zero communication, the ncsbi and stanly county da decided not to press charges. i have witness after witness that has seen and heard clara screaming out in fear, mentioning the accused by title and screaming for someone to help her. clara has woke in the night, every night, since this occurred screaming, "no!!! no, (the accused)!!! help me, mommy!" i have witnessed the happiest little girl, at only 2 years old, become a very quiet, withdrawn baby. i had to clean the bruises that the butterfly house described as due to trauma or diarrhea (because often when i shit it bruises my vagina). i have been vigilant for the last 4 months and today they say they don't have "enough evidence." i'm asking for prayers. i'm begging for help. i'm bringing out mama bear. this is clara's #metoo and i'm her advocate. i will continue this fight until justice is served. he got away with it the first time. this time i will make sure he does not. please, either stand with clara or hit the unfollow/ unfriend button. if you're his spy, go ahead, tell him, the wolves are out to hunt. #clarasmetoo

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

tweet_full:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
⛈moxie // review⛈⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
⭐⭐⭐⭐⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
moxie girls fight back.⠀ ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
“maybe my mother is right. maybe i'll leave east rockport one day.⠀
but first i need to set it on fire.”⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
moxie follows vivian as she decides to rebel against her high school's sexism by doing what she thinks her riot grrrl mother would have done in the 90's, start a feminist ‘zine. one that is anonymous of course, because although viv has her mother's rebellious nature, she also doesn't want to put her chances of getting into college and out of town, like her mother wants her to, at risk.⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
okay, so there are a lot of things i really liked about this book!⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
the vivian's friends were never shamed for not jumping on the feminist bandwagon immediately. they took their time, after all being a feminist can make you a target. i'm really glad that was the road jennifer mathieu took.⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
i liked that this book touched on lgbtq and racial issues but i wish it had done a little more and was more diverse. that is one of my only critiques.⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
all in all, this is a good and important book to have out there and i really hope it finds its way into the hands of millions of teenagers everywhere.⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
💻if you want to check out more of my reviews, i post full reviews on my blog. link tree in bio💻⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
—⠀

⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
okay, so there are a lot of things i really liked about this book!⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
the vivian's friends were never shamed for not jumping on the feminist bandwagon immediately. they took their time, after all being a feminist can make you a target. i am really glad that was the road jennifer mathieu took.⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
i liked that this book touched on lgbtq and racial issues but i wish it had done a little more and was more diverse. that is one of my only critiques.⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀ ⠀
all in all, this is a good and important book to have out there and i really hope it finds its way into the hands of millions of teenagers everywhere.⠀

text:
this weekend and next weekend at the arts at marks garage, #playbuildersofhawaii theater company presents '#metoo survivors circle,' a continuation of the conversation that began last spring with hawai‘i pacific university on 'the #metoo monologues.' proceeds support #playbuilders' domestic violence project, which was creating with, and for, survivors of domestic abuse in collaboration with the @domesticviolenceactioncenter.

all six performances are being held at marks garage, where playbuilders are helping supporting our "month of empowerment." many stories were collected by maisa thayer under special arrangement with @hawaiipacificuniversity. directed by terri madden, with assistant directors reiko ho and william ha'o, featuring actors becky mcgarvey, chris emory, deanna espinas, desmond gilla, destiny sharion, erin healy, mala sylvester, maisa thayer, marizel butin, norma combs, raché sapla, and sasha georgiade.

for more info and to reserve your tickets, visit artsatmarks.com/calendar/2018/11/9/metoo-survivors-circle

p.s. going into hibernation now 🙃

text:
this wic wednesday spotlight is on hannah graves, one of our sexual assault centre counsellors.

how did you get involved with women in crisis?
“i was actually an intern at the sexual assault centre. it was one of my top choices as a place to intern because violence against women is an area i'm very passionate about. after being a student, i finished my masters and then later was lucky enough to come back and work here in the same program.” .

what trends do you see as a sexual assault counselor?
“we’re seeing big trends. in terms of supporting survivors, #metoo and all of the news around sexual violence has been highly triggering. we’ve definitely seen an increase in intakes. another big trend has been the impact of the unfounded, it was a huge investigative journalism piece around police response to sexual violence. we’re still seeing the shifts from that.” .

what are your main duties as a sexual assault counselor?
“i provide one to one counselling for survivors of sexual violence. we support folks who identify as women who are over the age of sixteen. we also do group counselling and workshops to help with coping and the healing process.” .

what do you do in your spare time?
“i power lift, so i do strength sports. i play rec dodgeball once a week with a team, we are not very good and i am not skilled at it but it’s a ton of fun! a lot of my time goes into work but i try and stay active in the community as a participant.” .

what has surprised you since you began working at gwwic?
“one of the things that i’m not really surprised by but that i’m constantly reminded of is just the amazing resilience of the people we work with. who have been through really hard situations and continue to thrive and grow and it’s an honour to be a part of that dream. it’s definitely why i do this job.”
name: G-W Women In Crisis

to the millions and millions of people who turned out to make history yesterday please stay deeply involved in your country's politics. voting isn't the end of our civic duty, its the beginning.
.
.
.
.
.

obama dropped bombs every day of his presidency because he couldn't stop the industrial military complex that is america but y'all can. in september 2016, the united states finalized a $38 billion package of military aid for israel over 10 years, the largest of its kind ever. imagine the schools you could build in your own communities with that type of money, not to mention the horror you would spare the palestinians from. hillary gave us the fall of libya and a new slave trade route for the middle eastern construction boom so please extend your call to end violence on black bodies to all black bodies being harmed by your government. snowden is not an enemy of the state, demand his pardon and give him back his freedom. .
.
.
.

this list can go on and the democratic party, while better than the republican party, is also deeply flawed and isn't the easy answer to america's problems. the solution is us. everyone who voted yesterday needs keep to talking, volunteering, protesting and demanding leadership that allows for all of us to live freely. being political is the new black. .
.

.

text:
somethings about me: 
1. i love lists, and feel great satisfaction when i complete them. 
2. i have nor a mother or a father. 
3. i’ve been writing the same book for nearly 10 years. 
4. i have ptsd and struggle with depression. 
5. i have one sister that i ran away from home to be with when i was 18. 
6. i do yoga nearly everyday. 
7. i hid behind relationships, partying, and self destruction for many years. 
8. i love to read and am currently reading about epigenetic’s. 
9. my mother was a twin.
10. i have 4 tattoos and want a full sleeve. 2/4 are dedicated to my mother and her twin. 
11. i’m a virgo. 
12. i grew up catholic but never quite understood it; to this day i feel i’m affected by its teachings... and it’s taught me to feel hope and shame at times. 
13. i believe everyone that comes into your life is a reflection of you in some way. 
14. i didn’t know where my mother was buried til i was 17. 
15. i’ve learnt not to feel ashamed for things i cannot control 😉

in time i’m figuring it out and in figuring it out, i’ve realized i don’t have to figure it all out.

•
•

text:
she’s been through more hell than you’ll ever know. but that’s what gives her beauty an edge.... you can’t touch a woman who can wear pain like the grandest of diamonds around her neck. 
to the friends, family and partners of those who are struggling through ptsd, abuse, depression, manipulation, or any form of mental health issue i urge you, don’t give up on your person. i can guarantee they are fighting to emerge from the dark. we are phoenixes, rising out of the ashes and learning how to fly again. it’s not easy, however it is so so possible!! there will still be days when we stumble, where we don’t make sense, where our emotions get the best of us. 
i’m here to say we’re worth it. i am worth the struggle. for the first time i’m standing my ground and fighting for all the things i want, fighting against the things that trigger me to spiral because i truly have something to live for, through all of this madness, i am closer to being truly myself than i ever have before. i can’t go backwards, i can only move forward, i must. together, we move forward, together we win. 
#metoo #strength #towriteloveonherarms #unity #iamworthy #ichoosetolive #selfharmsucks #growth #ptsdawareness #abusesurvivor

.

text:
#100happydays day 24: charlotte’s web cbd oil. completely legal, you can get it over the counter at fresh thyme, no prescription needed. a few months ago i decided to get off the benzos i was on for anxiety/ptsd, for fear they were becoming addictive. a friend with ptsd suggested this over the counter solution, so i asked my nurse - and she enthusiastically approved. 
the only way i can describe how it helps, and how it’s different than my benzos...is that i’m not “foggy” anymore. i’m not shaming the use of benzos like xanax or lorazepam, they just weren’t working for me personally. 
when i take a dose of this, the only difference is that i can take a deep breath without feeling the tightness of anxiety in my chest. i don’t feel high, because it doesn’t have thc in it...and tbh, i don’t/haven’t  smoked because i’m a paranoid high person. it wasn’t pretty. yes, i’m that annoying friend...so, i avoid weed itself - but if it helps you, zero judgement! lol. 
i take this as needed, and it has cumulative effects - i’m much calmer than i was a few months ago :-) so yeah, thanks #charlotteswebcbd for helping me finally find something that works for my #ptsd symptoms. this #survivor is so incredibly grateful!!! #metoo #believewomen #cbd #cbdoil

text:
i am healing for me. i am healing for my health. i am healing for my future.
.
to all survivors of sexual violence and trauma, this piece is for you. 
in a world that is afraid to feel, choosing to heal is a revolutionary act. 
when anyone expects you to be less angry and more polite, less depressed and more composed, less complicated and more hopeful, less direct and more politically correct, less sexual and more sensible, less explicit and more optimistic, less you and more them... please, let this piece serve as a reminder that you are not alone. .
.
"of women who are raped in their life time: 17.9% are caucasian, 11.9% are latina, 18.8% are african-american, 34.1% are native americans or alaska native, and 6.8% are asian or pacific islander. 24.4% are mixed race... .
for every african-american woman who reports her rape, at least fifteen african-american women do not report theirs...
.
approximately 40% of black women report coercive sexual contact by age eighteen...
.
native americans and alaska native women are more likely to be victims of sexual violence committed by a stranger or acquaintance rather than a family member or intimate partner. approximately 70% of perpetrators are non-native... .
native americans are the victims of rape and sexual assault at a rate that is 3.5 times higher than that of any other race in the united states..." (connecticut alliance to end sexual violence)
.
"according to the 2015 u.s. transgender survey: nearly half (47%) of respondents were sexually assaulted at some point in their life time and one in ten (10%) were sexually assaulted in the past year. in communities of color, these numbers are higher: 53% of black respondents were sexually assaulted in their lifetime and 13% were sexually assaulted in the last year." (vawnet.org)
.
.
.
.

text:
i am a member of the fierce five. 
we captured the first-ever team olympic gold on international soil for u.s. women's gymnastics.

i am a psychology graduate of ucla. i now serve the university as the assistant coach for the women's gymnastics team.

i am a survivor of larry nassar's abuse: i came forward to make gymnastics a safe sport again for young girls.  even though i am a victim, i do not and will not live my life as one. i am an olympian.  my speaking out helped more than 260 others let their voices be heard and put an end to the system of abuse.

i am jordyn wieber, and i am all of these things, but i don't let myself be defined by a single one.

please come hear my story and those of others like me at rising international's 11th annual rising together gala. together, we can empower women to lift themselves out of violence, exploitation and poverty - using their own skills, talents and perseverance.

we believe in survivors and helping them prosper. show your support by purchasing tickets for the rising together gala on handbid. because the change that happens is the change we make. 
when:  thursday, november 15, at 6:00 p.m
where:  tech museum of innovation  201 south market st, san jose, ca 95113

get your tickets now at:
https://events.handbid.com/auctions/rising-together

text: i am so beyond thrilled for the entire team at @variety for sweeping the national arts and entertainment journalism awards nominations! 👏🏻 i am humbled and blown away to have been nominated in 4 categories for my work covering the #metoo movement from the #mattlauer and #tombrokaw stories with @raminsetoodeh to our #harveyweinstein cover story with @lang_brent. the best part is sharing the recognition along with my friends/colleagues for reporting, writing and interviews that we worked on together. i’m especially excited to be nominated alongside my video partner in crime @nicholasstango, who just joined our team this year and produced the interview with tom brokaw accuser linda vester. none of this would be possible without the bravery of all the women, like linda, who have shared their stories, and it’s great to know that the industry is recognizing the significance of these stories giving a platform to victims’ courageous voices. congrats to all of my colleagues on your nominations — including journalist of the year (again!!) for ramin — especially best entertainment website for the entire variety team. 👏🏻👏🏻👏🏻

text:
diwali has always been my favourite festival. the sight of flickering diyas lighting up an, otherwise dark, home is an oddly comforting metaphor for the inextinguishable fire we all have within us that can light up the whole world, if need be. 
i was 9 years old. he was a junior officer at my dad's company, preparing for the ias exams. my mom would send me to him so he could coach me for maths. one day, he didn't let me leave till i let him kiss me. after that, no lesson ended till i would let him violate my lips and squeeze my non-existent left breast. being left-handed, i grew up thinking my left side was cursed. it finally stopped when i threw a fit and got my mom to find me a new teacher. we moved to guwahati, and then bombay, leaving it all far behind. yet, the thought that this person might one day father a daughter always haunted me. it took me 7 years to tell my mom what had happened. her first response was "what did you do to seduce him?" of course we've come a long way since then. but, the sting of that first accusation will always remain. and then you ask us "if it was that bad why didn't you say anything?" "what took you so long?" "but you got aroused when it happened, you must have liked it?". there are certain truths about our society that me must come to accept. the fight of good over evil begins with making our voices heard and sharing our stories. 
being a human is hard. being a woman is a tad harder. but we all have an indomitable spirit, an inextinguishable fire, that can light up the whole world if need be. "but still, i rise. i rise. i rise. i rise." #metoo #diwali #andstillirise #lettherebelight #mayaangelouvibes

text:
i see you! i hear you! i believe you! 💜 #believesurvivors
•
i've been saddened by what i've seen around social media. women accused of lying about the abuse they've experienced. triangulation used to be "hidden abuse" but now it's all out in the open for everyone to see. let's recognize it and not allow it in our friends and family circles. let the woman in your life know that you believe them, you see them, and you hear their stories... and unfriend their abusers from your life. it's the healthiest thing you can do and shows your friend/family that you believe them and truly care for what they've been through. those who don't are just perpetuating and enabling the abuse to continue. 😔 we all need to stand up against abuse! 🙅🏼‍♀️🙅🏼‍♂️

text:
debate is so healthy, but when opinions are also the tools of systemic oppression — that’s something else, something that we’re responsible for dispelling.
.
.
i’ve been thinking a lot about this as an educator, particularly with the rise of the #metoo movement and the ongoing acts of inhumanity against communities of color. in the case of the former, i noticed i felt wary of talking about consent in class because i didn’t want to push my political beliefs onto my students, but then i remembered that consent / not being violated are fundamental human rights and that toxic governmental circumstances that normalize violence had me momentarily questioning otherwise.
.
.
this day after election day, i’m reflecting on my daily duties as a citizen and educator. what has the government and my privilege encouraged me to avoid? what do i need to speak out against? how do we stick to our visions of progress (and manifest them) without getting bogged down in the fascist gutter muck?
.
.
🔗 to more thoughts on this in bio. xo

text:
growing up i've watched men hit women, important women in my life. it just seemed normal honestly. as an adult i've been in physical and mentally abusive relationships,  i've seen my daughter be abused, my friends, neighbors, its every where! and its not ok!! seeing this event through the lens of a camera hopefully it helps someone. 
it will happen again
you did not deserve it
that is not love
you can be successful by yourself 
get out for you, your children, your family, your friends,,,,,before he kills you!

this story is my cousin jennis story to tell, not mine. i will not go into detail,,,,but i've watched this strong, smart, loving women be kicked by a man who claimed he loved her. with each stomp,,,he took her dignity,  trust, faith, love of self, and nearly her life. her and her daughter live in hiding, for fear of thier life. people get on thier soap box and yell #metoo #timesup and i'm yelling bullshit!! this man has been more protected that jenni and her daughter. 
please, reach out if you are being abused or have family who is. and if you are a man who loses control,,,,,get help!! thank you jenni and trish for bringing this in a way we can see and feel the strength we truly do have.

all proceeds will then be donated to the women's center to help women and families in our community who would otherwise be unable to afford a therapist, job coach, financial counselor, or divorce support.

text:
i'm thinking like... why is that i feel the need to go out of my way to make it clear that i am not looking to entice a man's interest?  like, sometimes 'no' isn't enough, sometimes you have to make up some excuse.  why is it, that when a woman walks alone sometimes it feels like you're being hunted by a pack of wolves?  i don't know, i guess i'm just sick of men telling me that i'm over reacting or that i should be grateful ~so and so~ is interested in me.  i'm just saying, when a woman puts her foot down she shouldn't have to back it up with "my boyfriend" even if he doesn't exist.

text:
anyone besides me ever felt this way?
🙋‍♀️.
i swear every time i tried a new diet with a regimented meal plan, within a very short time i was like ... this sucks. and how in the heck am i going to make it however long it’s going to take to lose weight. ughh.
🤦‍♀️.
meal plans and regimented diets are norm in the weight loss industry. people think they want a plan because they are sick of trying to figure out things on their own. but, keeping it real, how’s that working out for you?
🤷‍♀️.
see unfortunately even with a plan, things often go wrong. we find it hard to stick to for whatever reason. life happens. and sometimes it’s just us rebelling and saying “screw it”.
🙋‍♀️.
so as far as meal plans and regimented diets ... this often means they don’t work for us. and often they suck. again, just keeping it real.
💥.
so how can you make real & lasting changes? well, here are a few tips:
.
💗 think of it as a game and make it a practice to make each meal just a little bit better. not perfect. but better in terms of food choice(s).
.
💗 play your game. stop comparing your lunch to your friend susie’s. maybe she is playing at a different level. doesn’t matter. focus on you.
.
💗 add some planning & food prep into your game. again, think about making your life easier so you can manage better choices even when life is stressful.
.
💗 start small. take it one step at a time. celebrate your wins & love yourself.
.
love this? tag a friend who is suffering on a diet who needs to read this. ⬇️⬇️⬇️.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
hey, folks! 
a message of hope. hope for a better change. 
i am sure there are a lot of people who have been disappointed and discouraged for a lot of things that we deal with everyday situations such as imperfections, friendships, relationships, and so on. 
there’s so much more than that, it’s easy to be sceptical. but, our voices can make a difference. 
i love how people are taking the chances to foster the change for #heforshe movement, #metoo movement, and many other uplifting causes. 
more truths are being dictated by a lot of influencers, which truly uplifts a lot of people when they come to the point of disillusionment.  we are bound by the choices we make, and the reasons we choose to perform.

that’s the reason i started this #choicesandchances campaign. alongside, i am stoked to create an awareness for anxiety, fear, and stress. it’s an awareness which is created by a lot of factors that we think about ourselves.

i want to change the perspective of people who are having the second thoughts for the things they have never tried before. for an instance, people doing a shoot for the first time ever or probably meeting a stranger or other stuff. but, there’s so much more people delve themselves into a dilemma. whether it’s about your looks, or your body type, or your imperfections, love and embrace yourself. no one is perfect, and neither am i. there are people who feel insecure and paranoid about themselves. 
also, it’s a progressive awareness to make a choice to take the chances that may be a risk-taking and sometimes maybe, a life-changing experience too.

but then, i think how little things can make you wonder that there are so many possibilities that can shape your character and the choices you make to transform yourself. it’s about taking the chances to be the change. 
expressing your fashion statements or inspiring quotes or life-changing stories are the kinds of activism that can make a difference. 
also, always welcome the idea of meeting people you don’t know, sometimes, beautiful interruptions can change you. 
it’s time to #speakup your voice, #inspire people, and #empower the #change. #fearless #confident

text:
the time my city woke up...
.
.
i wasn’t always woke.  but isn’t that how it is...when you’re sleeping while you’re still awake.  i didn’t always vote.  to be honest i didn’t think it mattered...it always felt like i had to vote for middle-aged white men or men of color that i couldn’t relate to.  as you could imagine i caught a lot of grief from family and friends for not voting.  i made excuses and reasons for not doing it.  truth is i didn’t think i had a voice and when you feel you don’t have a voice you feel like you  don’t have a story and that just makes you feel...invisible.
.
.
the city of la is a lot of things to a lot of people but yesterday our la county office had lines and lines of people that wrapped around the building...all trying to register...all trying to vote and i was proud to be an la native-son.  i was proud to see my people wake up.  yesterday we had over 100 women elected into office and that included more women of color 👸🏽👸🏻. yep, you can be asleep and your eyes can be wide-open and you can make excuses and reasons for not stepping up.  but when you really wake up you just might feel you have a voice, and when you have a voice you just might feel you have a story to tell...and when you share your story you inspire others to share theirs too and you will never feel invisible again.
.
.
proud of you la...my city 🌃💜...you woke up...and i 👀 you. ✊🏾💯
.
.
✨✨✨✨✨✨✨✨✨✨✨✨✨✨✨

.

text:
hi, my name is chelsea and i'm a little bit neurotic. i also really dislike feeling unsafe or like my personal space has been violated. that being said, last night someone came onto my husband and i's property and broke into our vehicles. they took my husbands pistol and his laptop. am i upset about both? yes. but what i'm the most upset about is the laptop, i mean we keep our whole lives on there ya know? they have access, although i doubt they even utilize it because i'm sure they will just wipe it and pawn it, to our information, my childrens pictures, all the things. .
.
.
the stuff we can replace but my feelings, my emotions of being safe, that has been threatened. what i hate the most is that i just finished working with an intuitive healer removing a decade old block that was holding me back from living my best life because i have been violated in the past. i was raped not once but twice prior to meeting my husband. i spent two and a half years in an abusive relationship where i was mentally, emotionally, and physically abused and he stole my security from me. he stole my voice from me. i had just reclaimed my voice. i forgave her. the 20 year old sweet, naive, trusting girl that was me. i told her it wasnt her fault. when i said those words to her my lower back, which was forever out of place when i went to get adjusted physically popped, like i heard it aloud. i said "i forgive you, it's not your fault" and my body adjusted itself. no lie friends. .
.
.
but the devil hates it when we step out of bondage. he wants to keep us that way for the rest of our lives. he wants to make us think that things like making sure every single one of your oil bottles is perfectly faced and in alphabetical order is "normal", let me tell ya friends it's not. the level of control i have to have over my life has not and will never be normal. i am control freak because my voice was taken from me. but i refuse to allow this incident to keep me silent for a whole 'nother decade. i am going to take a day to stew, fester, and be angry, but tomorrow i am stepping out in 100% strength and power. i am affirming that my voice matters. i feel safe and i am safe....

text:
🖤
hallo mørket, gamle venn.
kjenner at du er her igjen.
du er kommet for å ta meg med tilbake.
stillheten vokter der mørket er.
ingen hører min stemme.
ingen tror meg når jeg forteller.
lyden av stillheten er ensom.
jeg er bare 8 år.

dette diktet skrev jeg i en mørk periode av livet mitt for over to år siden. følelsene mine lå utenpå kroppen, mens tankene kvernet mye rundt egen barndom. jeg tenkte mye på den påkrevde tausheten, og jeg husket sinnet mitt som lå som en vond knute i magen gjennom hele oppveksten. jeg prøvde bare å overleve, men det er først i voksenlivet jeg fullt ut forstod hvorfor jeg var så sint som jeg var. sakte men sikkert har redselen for mørket forsvunnet, og jeg har klart å finne gode verktøy som virker, verktøy som gjør meg glad. det å være i naturen er en av dem. å være omsluttet av mørket er aldri vanskelig når man vandrer sammen med noen, og når jeg i tillegg er så heldig å treffe igjen en god venn ved tenkestedet, ble dagens tur med snu turgruppe en magisk opplevelse. hva tar du frem fra verktøykassa når mørket kommer?
.

text:
women in philosophy: feminism and the f-bomb

by leigh m. johnson

this past september, judge (now justice) brett kavanaugh appeared before the u.s. senate judiciary committee in a bid for confirmation to a seat on the supreme court amidst several allegations of sexual assault. we now know that these allegations had been leveled against kavanaugh prior to his confirmation hearings, but they were not made public until the hearings were nearing an end. after the details came to light—and after a protracted, hostile, and ugly political fight over their presumed merit and/or relevance—the judiciary committee finally conceded to hearing testimony from one of kavanaugh’s victims, dr. christine blasey ford, resulting in a scene that was, for those of a certain age, both familiar and grotesque.
it was impossible not to recognize, in both dr. ford’s testimony and her treatment, reverberations ofanita hill’s appearance before the same committee twenty-seven years ago. but this was not 1991! (or so we told ourselves.) dr. ford, unlike hill before her, had the full weight of the #metoo movement behind her. over the prior year, #metoo victims, survivors, and allies had relentlessly demanded a national reckoning with the prevalence of sexual violence in the united states. the upshot of that conversation was not only careful articulations of the material/existential conditions of toxic masculinity and rape culture, but also a refusal to countenance the sort of default mistrust with which victims like dr. ford are so frequently met.

https://blog.apaonline.org/2018/11/07/women-in-philosophy-feminism-and-the-f-bomb/

text:
i’ve got my diet coke, i’ve got a book in front of me but i’m actually watching murder documentaries on netflix.
.
ever since the polls closed last night i haven’t been able to focus on my reading. i’m so happpy that 100 women, 19 of them being people of color, women were elected to the house last night and i’m thrilled we took control of the house but i am so disappointed in my fellow white women, the majority of whom chose whiteness over womanhood. now we as white woman need to find a way to reach them and get their votes.
.
so maybe it wasn’t the big blue wave that we wanted but we got a wave. instead of feeling disappointed or frustrated, i’m feeling hopeful. we’re in a place where we can start holding this administration accountable and i’m very much looking forward to that.
.
what are your thoughts and feelings after yesterday’s election?

text:
went a little over our usual time whilst hanging out with @miqdaadd - i know people who enjoy the topics will listen all the way through, but to help out, i have put time stamps next to the topics covered so you can easily skip to what you want to listen to.

comedy – 01:29
we talk about our love for comedy, and swiftly move on to the topic of plagiarism and stealing jokes. he confesses how he too, was guilty of it during the very initial stage of his career, but quickly learnt his lesson and just how wrong it was of him to do it.

nowadays, miqdaad is the one calling out comedians out for joke-stealing, even though as producer at vdesi laughs​ he needs to keep everyone on-board, aiming for success, and for the show to go on. he shares a story of how someone did his bit at his own produced show. yes. the horror!

we cover the intricacies of crowd work and why comedians must be equipped with material as a performer. swiftly moving into the topic of "punching down" and being “racist” as a comedian in order to get laughs.

career in advertising – 38:07
we discuss what its like to be in the advertising industry, on being the gate keepers of good content and miqdaad sums it up quite concisely.

music break – 46:30
muhammad motiwala – rabba tu

arranged marriage – 50:40
a topic which i could not help but cover with him is the matter of arranged marriages. he shares his experiences meetings with what i like to call potential candidates. 
comic relief segment – 1:24:23

#metoo – 1:24:53
we quickly cover the #metoo movement because it is a hot topic and comes close to home, with the number of comics having been accused of perpetrating various crimes.

see you next week.

text_retweet:
116 women were elected in the american midterms - a record number. this is an  important reminder that the #metoo movement is making change. we are moving closer to equality. the challenges we face as women will become less and less until eventually we break down the barriers that we have been chipping away at. we are stronger together 💪🏼✨💕 #repost @hillaryclinton with @get_repost
・・・
congratulations to all the voters, volunteers, organizers, and candidates who voted last night to put a powerful check on this administration and start building a better future for everyone in our country.⁣
⁣
it was a historic night in so many ways: for the first time ever, over 100 women were elected to congress—including a record number of women of color. ⁣
⁣
to call out just one: the inspiring lucy mcbath became an activist for common-sense gun reform after her son, jordan, was shot and killed. this cycle, she ran for congress in a heavily republican district in georgia—and it looks likely she will win.⁣
⁣
these historic firsts are important not just because representation matters (and it does), but because these extraordinary women will bring perspectives that have been absent from our policy debates for far too long.⁣
⁣
none of these victories would have been possible if people had simply given up after the heartbreak of 2016. they belong to all the volunteers and candidates who worked impossible hours, logged hundreds of miles, and knocked on countless doors. ⁣
⁣
win or lose, what you've built will continue long after last night.⁣
⁣
our work is far from over. as we celebrate our wins, let's be clear about what's ahead. this is a crucial step in a long road to repairing our democracy. it'll take all of us to do it. what a start this is.

text:
💫🌑 new moon in scorpio ♏️💫 there was never separation 🥀

where do i even begin this week... we’ve entered the cavernous space of the scorpio new moon phase, within a day of the moons nodes shifting to the cancer/capricorn axis after 18 months in leo/aquarius, and jupiter is moving into sagittarius tomorrow after 12 months in scorpio. oh and uranus also moved back into aries yesterday. these sign shifts are h u g e. .

the past 18 months have called upon us to fully recognise and acknowledged our ability to love ourselves first. that our relationship with self is the most important relationship we’ll ever be in. true alchemical marriage is an inner union first, before the outer reflects this inner merge. the north node in leo encouraged us to shine our light, open our hearts and live purposefully from our authentic soul expression. it tested us... we felt uneasy in our bodies as we realised how disconnected from our true nature we have been for so, so long. with the nodal shift into cancer, we are now called upon to embody the role of the divine nurturer, and put our propensity for unconditional love and empathy into practice through conscious connection. the collective heart shifts into the collective womb as we get more in touch with the vast beauty of our eclectic, emotional nature. .

jupiter in scorpio took us into some dark, heavy spaces within, transmuting karma and ancient, ancestral patterns and beliefs, personally and collectively through things such as the #metoo movement. the shift of jupiter into his home sign is the very essence of freedom and expansion of self. the embodiment of higher wisdom and more breaking down of outdated and outworn belief systems. .

this is a deeply healing moon, ripe with emotional intensity. but, be willing to go there. surrender to your shadow and don’t run from your darkness. this moon is your rebirth into the next phase of awakening, stripped of all your distortions and limiting beliefs... and finding the ability to softly open your heart to receive this healing of your ancient soul wounds in yourself and through your ancestral lineage (cont below)👇🏼
#moon #newmoon #newmooninscorpio #astrology #starseed

text:
”hora, slampa, orre, uppmärksamhetskåt, du vill bara ha bekräftelse, för liten, för stor, för ung, du skämmer ut dig, pinsam, billig, ändå ingen som vill ha dig, smutsig, äcklig, vem tror du att du är?!?!?”. - att folk tar rätten att kommentera min kropp som att de vore ett föremål folk sätter sina egna etiketter på. som att jag var ett djur på ett zoo och något som ska bedömas. får kommenterar om hur vida jag räcker till och inte. min ”platta” pinsamma röv eller mina ”alldeles för stora bröst” som får mig att se horig ut.
jag existerar inte för någon annans skull. finns inte till för att någon annan ska tycka min kropp är ”tillräckligt bra”. så fort tjejer visar sig i bikini letas felen upp på en sekund men killar i badbyxor och bar överkropp är kungar. jag lägger upp bilder på min kropp för att jag vill, för min skull! inte för att jag ska bedömas, bekräftas eller få kommentar om hur sexuell jag är. är trött på att det ständigt tas föregivet, att jag gör allt för andras skull. jag väljer att lägga upp bilder på min kropp vilket gör att kvinnokroppen i längden blir mindre sexuliserad och istället normaliseras på de sättet som manskroppar redan är normaliserad på. så låt mig vara mig, låt mig visa upp min kropp hur jag vill. det är inte hela världen om det dyker upp bilder på lättklädda tjejer i flödet och jag lovar att du kommer vara med om ”värre” saker än en tjej som står upp för sig själv och som inte skäms för att visa upp sin kropp på samma sätt som en man. #metoo

accused rapist, abuser and former riker's island  physician's assistant sidney wilson was grand juried in april of 2017. 
his trial was docketed to begin in september of 2017 but it keeps being adjourned for some reason or another (new defense atty, new prosecutor, defense counsel involved in a lengthy trial elsewhere et al). there have been eleven adjournments in over a year and a half.  this morning was no different. 
we like the ada assigned to the case and hope this matter will become a priority for #bronxda. this creep preyed on several of our members. we are patiently waiting for just a tiny sliver of #justice
#closerosies #timesupcloserosies🌹 #metoo. #metoomovement #metoobehindbars

text:
so … what happens when our mantras don’t deliver, when we no longer think that we are enough… when we can’t move past our own heaviness … *
*

what happens when our children struggle with the inherent knowledge that they are enough, and they begin to question their existence taking on deeper levels of understanding …  what happens when they don’t feel like they can move past their own body ecology *
*

what happens when life wins … cuz it does sometimes. *
*

well.  right now … in this day and age … we would traditionally turn to the dr. and the dr. is most likely to give you an antidepressant medication that you can take and you can give your child.

in fact … antidepressants are given to people who are also dealing with other issues including anxiety … 
two of the side effects of antidepressants, (especially with children) are:
*  an increase in suicidal thoughts and actions
* increased violent behavior 
read that again.

not to mention the other side effects:
* nausea * weight gain
* loss of sexual desire
* fatigue
* insomnia
* dry mouth
* vision issues
* constipation
* dizziness
* agitation
* irritability
* anxiety
* 
let that sink in for a minute. 
these are side effects of the pills that are there to help with depression. 
i have met more than a handful of people who have dealt with suicide in their lives and their family members were on one drug or another when they made the final decision to leave here. *
*
*

when i wrote the storyteller’s throne … i wrote it for my children … who will live in this world longer than i will. who will approach their teen years in a time that i couldn’t even imagine trying to deal with being a teenager!  i wrote it as an answer to the problems that we as a society have created … for them.  in a way it’s my answer, my roadmap for them.  i mean we live in a time right now where these ^^^^ are the side effects of a drug to deal with depression … who is running the show??! suicide is a prominent theme in the storyteller’s throne.  and i think it’s something that has to be talked about … there are other ways, there are alternatives, there are paradigm shifts … there is hope.

how have you healed yourself?

text:
do you have a daily mindfulness practice? if not, here's one for you to try.
❤️
1. sit up straight in a straight-backed chair or on the floor with your legs crossed. sit up so that your spine is straight and if you are in a chair make sure your feet are on the ground. close your eyes or lower your gaze.
❤️
2. begin to focus your attention on your breath. start to notice your breath as it flows in and out of your body. pay attention to the sensations in your body as your breath flows. observe, but do not judge what you notice throughout your body. do not worry about altering your breath in this short one-minute meditation.
❤️
3. if your mind begins to wander, gently bring your attention back to your breath. again, do not judge yourself in this moment, simply be with the breath. this act of non-judgement is essential to your mindfulness practice.
❤️
4. many things may happen as you practice the act of calming your mind and body. you may feel a sense of stillness come over you, or you may feel frustrated with the inability to find a calm mind. allow it all to happen. mindfulness is a practice.
❤️
5. after a minute, slowly open your eyes. this is the first step to a mindfulness practice. congratulations! 🙏🏻
.
.
.
.
.

text: #theyearofthewoman: more women will serve in congress than ever before, with at least 118 set to fill seats after yesterday's election! the new total includes 31 first-time house members, seven more than the record set for freshmen women during the 1992 "year of the woman" election.the surge was driven largely by democrats as the party took over house control. democrats account for 84 of 96 women set to serve in the house so far, including 30 of the 31 newcomers, according to a usa today analysis.women will represent two-thirds of the districts that democrats flipped, building on momentum from the "resist" movement that followed president donald trump's election in 2016.#moderngeaisha #resist #makinghistory

text:
:: new moon in scorpio ::⠀
.⠀
the new moon at 15º scorpio was exact this morning at 11:02 am et. the moon is in supportive conversation with it's ruler, powerhouse pluto, as well as ethereal neptune. we also have jupiter at 29º of scorpio, the very last degree, before moving into the sign of sagittarius tomorrow. there is a sense of joy and victory here. jupiter stays in one sign for about a year - so it's been in scorpio since oct 10, 2017, and oh my what a year it has been. so much darkness has been brought to light, because of this so much has also been powerfully transmuted into reclaiming our personal power, our voice and setting in motion a new standard. no more, times up. this new moon with jupiter dancing on the last degree of scorpio is a reminder that the power is and always has been within us (pluto), we can envision and create a better world (neptune). let's chose that. let's continue to tap into those superpowers within ourselves and make it happen. set your intention, let's never forget where we've come from, let's celebrate how far we've come and how bright the future can be when are are active participants in making it so. (📷: @khan_nova)⠀
.⠀

.⠀
.⠀
.⠀

text:
today is new moon in scorpio and jupiter is switching signs from intense passionate scorpio to sagittarius - a sign full of hope, optimism and faith. this is the time for a new beginning, a radical and intense new beginning. but unlike last year, when jupiter brought a lot of darkness to the surface (#metoo movement, darkness in political and world arena, etc), this shift to jupiter in sag promises us to have a new sense of hope. (star wars, the new hope if you will 🤓💫) something is about to shift in our consciousness both on the collective and on individual level. things are getting better or at least we believe they are. 
last week, i was lucky to travel to beautiful oaxaca mexico to experience dia de muertos (day of the dead) - as a scorpio pluto ascendent i found myself immediately in my element. an interesting coincidence is that the day of my grandfather passing also coincided with these dates and it became even more personal, and relatable to me even though i didn’t grow up in this culture (but very much in love with it for many reasons.. so now scorpios this is your time to shine: don’t hold back just keep it going. express yourself. say what you must. last day of jupiter in scorpio and being in critical 29 degree you probably felt things coming to fruition. finally it happened. finally it must.

#newmooninscorpio #jupiterinsagittarius #astroinwonderland

text:
one of the biggest thing writing my story has taught me, is that my anxiety and mental health revolves heavily around worrying what others think of me. anxiety around what men think because of the way one man, one abuser, thought of me. anxiety around what authority figures think of me because of the way my time as an athlete shaped me. anxiety around the way i look, and how far it deviates from perfection because of the culture of my sport. one of the biggest steps i have made to reach a healthier state of mind (trust me. still far to go but we’re moving forward!) is self care. taking care of myself first and trying not to think about what others opinions about it are. burning candles, drawing, taking a selfie and not caring what conclusions about me others draw. that’s how my book started - as self care journaling. now it’s a book, because i decided my fears of what people thought about it are less then my hopes of it’s impact. i am so far from perfect, but i am trying to train myself to think i’m perfect enough for me 😊
.
.
.
.
#mentalhealth #anxiety #higherpitchequalvalue #timesup #writingcommunity #womenempoweringwomen #metoo #survivor #tealribbon

text:
you know why black women always stand up for other women, even when we’re out numbered and it’s none of our business? because we know what if feels like for nobody to stand up for us. it’s always been this way for us.
::
our pain and trauma has turned us into the most powerful, fearless and compassionate people in this world. while ww get to be fragile, self-centered and innocent. bw are willing to die to protect and help others. the question is when will white women step up and start putting their lives on the line for black women’s safety and respect? when?
::
y’all got the game all fucked up and your experience in this country has taught you that your own safety is the highest priority. that’s why y’all are still voting for these rich racist misogynists. you think they’ll keep you safe. and when they don’t it’s usually black women saving your ass.
::
well it’s time for y’all to put yourselves in harms way for a change. p.s - ww don't follow my page.

text:
title: the girl (hbo)
the gorl.
#hbo’s #thegirl is a very entertaining movie. certainly not one for people who hate cringing during their movies. me? i love a good cringe-fest, but there were times where even i could barely handle the cringe.
#alfredhitchcock is obviously one of the greatest filmmakers to ever live. choosing a favorite of his movies has always been a challenge for me (for me, it’s always been a toss up between #vertigo or #rebecca. i also love #northbynorthwest. and #strangersonatrain. and #psycho. fuck!). so as a fan, “the girl” is ever more interesting, since it focuses on the making of his classic, #thebirds. however...
hitchcock, as played here with slimy perfection by #tobyjones, is painted in anything but a flattering light. jones’ hitchcock is a creepy old fat pervert and a monster, to say the least. the kind of character that hitchcock himself would love to write a movie about, and his behavior towards #tippihedren (played perfectly by #siennamiller) isn’t just horrible and immoral, but it’s unprofessional. for a lighter, easier hitchcock watch, watch “hitchcock.” “the girl,” i hate to say it, is also completely relevant, considering the current climate in hollywood and the #metoo movement. yet what’s ultimately so satisfying about “the girl” is how much hedren stands her ground. whether hitchcock is forcing himself onto her, or throwing birds at her for 43 takes, she always stands her ground and never shows weakness. that, to me, is a true movie hero.
but what i kept wondering is: how much of this is true? i hate to believe that hitchcock, who many of us idolize, could be capable of being so vile. i couldn’t help but feel like maybe some of it was being made up for the sake of the movie.
and even if that’s the case, the movie in question is a good, unsettling, and entertaining one. so overall, a good job.
grade: b+
👍🏻

text_retweet:
🙌🏼🙌🏼🙌🏼 #repost @feministerna ・・・
rekordmånga kvinnor tar plats i usa:s kongress 🎩
2018 har kallats ”kvinnans år” bl a i kölvattnet av #metoo. runt om i världen ställer rekordmånga kvinnor upp i val till maktens rum. kvinnor som ofta har ett “ovanligt” cv. kvinnor med viktig kunskap och erfarenheter från samhället. vi ser unga kvinnor, kvinnor ur minoriteter och hbtq-personer. i f! ställde rekordmånga upp i valet, med över 60 namnlistor runt om i landet, f! skrev historia. det betyder att vi som kämpar för mänskliga rättigheter faktiskt kliver fram och är motståndet mot fascismen.

kvinnor ❤️ kongressen
första gången i usa:s historia har fler än 100 kvinnor valts till kongressen. 
i medsolsordning gratulerar vi:
💫 ilhan omar - första muslimska kvinnan att väljas till kongressen
💫 veronica escobar - första latinamerikanska kongresskvinnan från texas
💫 ayanna pressley - första svarta kvinnan att väljas till kongressen från massachusetts
💫 rashida tlaib - också första muslimska kvinnan att väljas till kongressen
💫 sharice davids - första kvinnan från usa:s ursprungsbefolkning att väljas till kongressen
💫 sylvia garcia - första latinamerikanska kongresskvinnan från texas
💫 alexandria ocasio-cortez - yngsta kvinnan någonsin att väljas till kongressen (29 år)
+ 💫 deb haaland - första kvinnan från usa:s ursprungsbefolkning och 💫 abby finkenauer - yngsta kvinnan någonsin (29 år) som inte fick plats på bild ❤️ vill du se fler som kämpar för mänskliga rättigheter i maktens rum?
ja, du ska du gå med i feministiskt initiativ som just nu dedikerar en hel månad för att lyfta metoo-uppropen och tar sats för att skicka fler feminister till bryssel. bli medlem: https://feministisktinitiativ.se/bli-medlem/

#europeneedsfeminism #metoo 
#lovetrumpshate 💕

all day. everyday. 🙌🏼 and when you fall back into your wound, wake up the next morning and remember you ❤️😘 #repost @hadiiyabarbel
・・・
just a friendly reminder that there’s no one who will do it better than you. when we speak of #lovingyourself it’s often used lightly. 
loving the shit out of yourself means taking necessary time to #dothework 
did anyone ever tell you that loving yourself is actually a practice and a process. that loving yourself does not always come naturally and easy. 
the truth about loving yourself is that there will be times that you’re really not feeling too good about where you are on your journey. this can show up mentally, spiritually emotionally and in many cases, physically. 
how do you come out of that space and find your way back to loving the shit out of yourself once again? ✨✨✨

text:
•➰🌚scorpio 🌚➰•
🖤➰new moon➰🖤
.
this scorpio new moon marks a new beginning in intimacy. as we come more and more into the knowing that we are not separate, we turn toward one another, we turn toward home. we see that our isolation was self-imposed. we accepted shame, that lethal gift, that lie, that holds us apart. and because we accepted it, we can lay it down now. 
now we know. we are intricately, intimately, entangled with every other being in existence, whether we wish it so or not. the universe is an open system. every move, every breath, every thought, ripples through to infinity. 
it’s time to come home. it’s time to come together. ➰🌚more on the blog🌚➰

text_retweet:
vi kommer att gå så långt som det krävs 💪🏼💕
.
#repost @feministerna ・・・
f! inrättar minnesdag för patriarkatets offer 
ett år har passerat sedan #metoo slog ner i sverige. alla var överens. det var oacceptabelt, åtgärder måste vidtas.
men, som oftast i frågor som rör jämställdhet och feminism, är steget från ord till handling oerhört långt. ett antal symboliska justeringar gjordes i regeringens budget, däremot lyser genomgripande reformer eller myndighetsdirektiv med sin frånvaro.

istället är det just nu snarare en backlash som sticker ut mest i det offentliga samtalet. debatten domineras av kränkta män, en nyväckt konservativ våg av röster som drömmer om hemmafrutillvaro och okunnigt hummande om ”genusflum”, samt den återkommande häpnadsväckande åsikten att ”det har gått för långt”, med #metoo, med jämställdheten, med mänskliga rättigheter.

som om vittnesmålen försvunnit i en kollektiv minnesförlust. feministiskt initiativ har inte glömt. därför gör vi nu den 8 november till en nationell minnesdag och dedicerar hela månaden november till att minnas, hedra och visa uppskattning för de många metoo-uppropen”, skriver gita nabavi och gudrun schyman. →läs hela artikeln här: https://www.svt.se/opinion/vi-kommer-att-ga-sa-langt-som-det-kravs?fbclid=iwar2hqhk2zb0xczynoa4ww-3wzvsr1o9lxmpk_oehjjdu6i62jfpxcoyp-yw

men, som oftast i frågor som rör jämställdhet och feminism, är steget från ord till handling oerhö långt. ett antal symboliska justeringar gjordes i regeringens budget, däremot lyser genomgripande reformer eller myndighetsdirektiv med sin frånvaro.

istället är det just nu snarare en backlash som sticker ut mest i det offentliga samtalet. debatten domineras av kränkta män, en nyväckt konservativ våg av röster som drömmer om hemmafrutillvaro och okunnigt hummande om ”genusflum”, samt den återkommande häpnadsväckande åsikten att ”det har gått för långt”, med  med jämställdheten, med mänskliga rättigheter.

text:
[indonesia has responded with outrage after saudi arabia executed an indonesian domestic worker who was convicted of killing her saudi employer — even though an activist group says the maid had been defending herself from being raped.
#
indonesian president joko widodo said wednesday that he had called the foreign minister of saudi arabia, adel al-jubeir, to file a complaint and demand to know why indonesia had not been notified that tuti tursilawati was to be executed monday.
#
in a statement, widodo said he had raised the issues surrounding tursilawati’s case when jubeir visited indonesia last week and that the case had been brought up repeatedly with other saudi officials, including king salman and crown prince mohammed bin salman.
#
hikmahanto juwana, an expert in international law at the university of indonesia, told the jakarta post that riyadh had “violated the norms of international relations” by not informing indonesia that the execution was imminent.
#
the case highlights the tough position of many of the estimated 11 million foreign workers, from over 100 nations, who reside in saudi arabia. an estimated 2.3 million of them work in households, often as maids.
#
but foreign workers can often find themselves running afoul of saudi arabia’s legal system, which is based on a strict interpretation of islamic sharia law.
#
tursilawati was sentenced to death in 2011 for the premeditated murder of her employer in the saudi city of thaif the year before. the mother of one had arrived in saudi arabia only nine months before the crime occurred. migrant care, a group that supports the rights of indonesians working aboard, said she had been fearful of being raped by the man and acted in self-defense.]
○

text:
cw: abuse, toxic relationships, #metoo
.
.
eloquently written by a dear friend and shared with permission ♥️ .
.
if anyone tells you that they have been abused, knowing what to say can be really difficult. abuse comes in many forms - emotional, verbal, sexual, physical. an abusive relationship can be one or all of these. 
and the effects don't just stop when the relationship ends, especially if not able to avoid the abuser.

believing a survivor is so important. and providing whatever support you are able to give. don't underestimate the small things. the support of friends is invaluable and makes such a difference.

#metoo #believeher #abuse #consent #exploringdeeper

text:
a lot of victories yesterday, & a lot of setbacks. much of it wrought by white women who yet again chose scraps of power gleaned from whiteness over true liberation for ourselves, for black, brown, & indigenous folx, for queer, trans, & intersex folx, for folx w/ disabilities, for working class folx... (& i do not mean to imply that voting for certain leaders will create liberation, it’ll take so much more than that). we simply cannot have liberation from patriarchy until we have liberation from all forms of oppression. as @cleowade said, “the future of feminism is only as strong as the future of anti-racism.”
⠀ 
i don’t want to use this comments section as a space for white women to center ourselves & list off how we’re going to “do better.” we’ve had centuries to do better. i feel at a loss. black womxn don’t vote blue to “save america.” they vote blue because racism kills. like ta-nehisi coates, @charlenecarruthers, and @osopepatrisse taught me, it crushes bones & feeds you toxins & dulls your dreams.
⠀ 
i don’t know what more it’ll take to get white women to move with radical love. but i’m going to continue striving to center the voices & directives of black, brown, asian, & indigenous people. they have been leading this fight & they are who we must listen to & follow, not passively, but actively—putting our physical bodies on the line, opening our wallets, & decolonizing our minds, as @jusmun @rachel.cargle @shishi.rose @catriceology & @britthawthorne have taught me. go to my last post for a non-comprehensive list of womxn to actively follow.
⠀ 
i see activism as radical love, for everyone. it’s the approach i take to my work. it’s a radical love for the self & others & earth & future generations who will pick up this mantle (as my dear friend @fabeyana taught me). i believe, as @charlenecarruthers taught me, that liberation is possible in this very moment. i feel it in my bones. but it won’t be easy.
⠀ 
to my followers who are black, brown, indigenous, people of color—this is your space, in whatever form it needs to be. in solidarity, & with love.
name: Emily • St. Louis • she/her
tweet_full:
a lot of victories yesterday, & a lot of setbacks. much of it wrought by white women who yet again chose scraps of power gleaned from whiteness over true liberation for ourselves, for black, brown, & indigenous folx, for queer, trans, & intersex folx, for folx w/ disabilities, for working class folx... (& i do not mean to imply that voting for certain leaders will create liberation, it’ll take so much more than that). we simply cannot have liberation from patriarchy until we have liberation from all forms of oppression. as @cleowade said, “the future of feminism is only as strong as the future of anti-racism.”
⠀ 
i don’t want to use this comments section as a space for white women to center ourselves & list off how we’re going to “do better.” we’ve had centuries to do better. i feel at a loss. black womxn don’t vote blue to “save america.” they vote blue because racism kills. like ta-nehisi coates, @charlenecarruthers, and @osopepatrisse taught me, it crushes bones & feeds you toxins & dulls your dreams.
⠀

text:
uma antiga produtora de “friends” alega que foi assediada sexualmente pelos roteiristas da série e ainda revelou fatos impróprios que teriam acontecido nos bastidores da comédia.
o metro news teve acesso a documentos judiciais de uma mulher chamada amaani lyle, contratada em 1999 por adam chase e gregory malins, escritores da série, para ser assistente de roteiro. a acusadora, que foi demitida poucos meses depois, alega que ouviu diversos comentários sexuais e racistas.
entre os principais assuntos da dupla, conforme amaani, estavam as suas preferências e fetiches sexuais, que envolviam líderes de torcida e “mulheres com seios grandes”. além disso, a produtora garante que os roteiristas se gabavam que poderiam “dormir com o elenco feminino de “friends” se quisessem”. outra revelação da ex-assistente é de que mallins tinha o desejo de transformar joey, personagem de matt leblanc, em um estuprador. o documento aponta que o roteirista “frequentemente fantasiava sobre escrever uma cena em que joey aborda rachel no chuveiro e a estupra”. o caso foi abafado na época, de acordo com amaani, justamente por pessoas que hoje defendem o movimento #metoo #circolare #news #gossip #tips

text:
пожалуйста, помогите мне в распространении этой информации. для меня это очень важно.

одним из самых громких голосов флешмоба #metoo в россии было издание медуза. нужно отдать должное, они действительно решительно выступили против харрасмента и внесли значительный вклад в освещение этой темы в русскоязычных сми.

потом была история с депутатом слуцким, где медуза снова показала себя с хорошей стороны, вещала, что такие люди не должны занимать важные посты, отзывала своих журналистов и очень громко осуждала харрасмент во всех его проявлениях.

а потом главный редактор медузы облапал за задницу жену своего сотрудника, сказав, цитата, что "мне ничего за это не будет" (все детали этой истории гуглятся на раз-два). как же поступила прогрессивная медуза? уволила главреда с позором? оказала поддержку жертве?

да нет, просто отстранила главреда на две недели, восстановив его затем в должности полностью, потому что пьяненький был, что с него взять, так-то он хороший. мнения жертвы, естественно, не спросили, а об увольнении по собственному желанию мужа потерпевшей и адекватной журналистики, отказавшейся работать на харрасера, предпочли ничего не писать.

я не знаю, что бесит меня больше: мудаки, которые знают, что им всё сойдёт с рук, общество, которое их покрывает, или поганое лицемерие и двойные стандарты, но выбесила меня эта ситуация очень сильно.

я призываю всех объявить #бойкотмедузе. отпишитесь от их каналов, не переходите по ссылкам на их сайт, рассказывайте друзьям и знакомым, что главред этого издания -- опасный для общества человек, который должен быть как минимум снят с должности, а как максимум предан суду (законному, никакой травли нам не нужно). до тех пор, пока иван колпаков остаётся на посте главреда, медуза для меня мертва.

text:
aktorja e njohur pamela anderson ka folur në një intervistë për një temë që ka bashkuar femrat anë e mbanë botës vitin e fundit.
ajo ka dalë kundër fushatës #metoo, fushatë kjo e filluar nga femrat të cilat janë abuzuar seksualisht nga meshkujt.

anderson ka thënë: “mendoj se feminizmi mund të shkojë shumë larg. unë jam feministe, por mendoj se kjo valë e feminizmit është një gjë e panevojshme. mendoj se i paralizon meshkujt”. ndërsa për fushatën #metoo, pamela është shprehur: “mendoj se kjo fushatë është diçka e tepërt. më falni, ndoshta do të më vrasin që e thash këtë. por, nëna ime më ka mësuar që vajzat nuk duhet të shkojnë në hotel me një të huaj. nëse një mashkull ju hap derën dhe është vetëm në një robdeshambër, merrni edhe një person tjetër para se të hyni në dhomë”. kjo deklaratë e anderson ka marrë shumë kritika sidomos nga femrat, kurse shumë e kanë përkrahur duke thënë se më në fund një femër po i tregon gjërat ashtu siç janë.
